    "body": "<span class=\"solution-visible-txt\">All submissions for this problem are available.</span><h3>Problem statement</h3>\n<p>\n\tGopal is conducting an conducting an experiment to test his awesome theory.\n</p>\n<h3>Experiment Setup</h3>\n<p><img src=\"/download/extimages/ed4888c1a8895154a66ec4505d36af98.jpg\" alt=\"Experimental setup\" /></p>\n<p>Initially there are 3 containers <strong>C<sub>1</sub></strong>, <strong>C<sub>2</sub></strong>, <strong>C<sub>3</sub></strong> with equal volume of water in each container. All containers  will change their volume during the experiment and all containers are required to be filled throughout the experiment. Volume of <strong>C<sub>1</sub></strong> and <strong>C<sub>3</sub></strong> at any time <strong>t</strong> depends on external conditions like pressure, temperature etc. Volume of <strong>C<sub>2</sub></strong> depends on the volume of <strong>C<sub>1</sub></strong> and <strong>C<sub>3</sub></strong>.\n</p>\n<p>\n\tAt any time <strong>t</strong>, <strong>C<sub>1</sub></strong> and <strong>C<sub>3</sub></strong> may expand or shrink. If any one or both the containers  (<strong>C<sub>1</sub></strong> and <strong>C<sub>3</sub></strong>) shrink, <strong>C<sub>2</sub></strong> will expand to accommodate the water received from the shrunken container/s. If any one or both the containers  (<strong>C<sub>1</sub></strong> and <strong>C<sub>3</sub></strong>) expand, <strong>C<sub>2</sub></strong> will shrink by giving water to the container/s which was expanded. Containers never shrink to negative volumes. So when volume of <strong>C<sub>2</sub></strong> becomes <strong>0</strong> and if any one the containers <strong>C<sub>1</sub></strong> and <strong>C<sub>3</sub></strong> is not yet filled then external water source is used.\n</p>\n<p>\nNow Gopal defines his awesome theory on <strong>Gopalency</strong> of water as,</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Gopalency</strong> exists between time <strong>T<sub>1</sub></strong> and <strong>T<sub>2</sub></strong> if and only if <strong>T<sub>2</sub></strong> >= <strong>T<sub>1</sub></strong> and volume of <strong>C<sub>2</sub></strong> should not be <strong>0</strong> at any time between <strong>T<sub>1</sub></strong> and <strong>T<sub>2</sub></strong> inclusive.</li>\n<li>For a time <strong>T<sub>1</sub></strong> and <strong>T<sub>2</sub></strong> if <strong>Gopalency</strong> exists, it is defined as<br />\n<pre> Gopalency = Vol. of water in C<sub>2</sub> at <strong>T<sub>2</sub></strong> - Vol. of water in C<sub>2</sub> at <strong>T<sub>1</sub></strong> \n</pre></li>\n</ul>\n\t\n<p>\n\tNow Gopal is tired after conducting lot of experiments, he needs your help to find the maximum <strong>Gopalency</strong> in each experiment conducted by him, using his observations.  \n</p>\n\n\n<h3>NOTE</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Water in the pipes is negligible.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>INPUT</h3> \n<p>\t\nFirst line of the input contains the <strong>T</strong>, number of experiments conducted by Gopal.\nIn observations of each experiment <br/>\nFirst line contains <strong>N</strong>, No. of seconds for which experiment was conducted starting from 0.\nNext <strong>N+1</strong> lines contains 2 integers <strong>V1<sub>i</sub></strong> and <strong>V3</strong><sub>i</sub>, Volume of water in <strong>C<sub>1</sub></strong> and <strong>C<sub>3</sub></strong> respectively in <strong>i</strong>th second.\n</br/></p>\n<h3>OUTPUT</h3>\n<p>\nOutput should contain <strong>T</strong> lines containing single integers <strong>MAX</strong>. where <strong>MAX</strong> is maximum Goaplency for <strong>i</strong>th experiment.\n</p>\n<h3>\nCONSTRAINTS</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>1 \u2264 <strong>T</strong> \u2264 10</li>\n<li>0 \u2264 <strong>N</strong> \u2264 10<sup>6</sup></li>\n<li>0 \u2264 <strong>V<sub>1</sub>,V<sub>3</sub></strong> \u2264 10<sup>6</sup></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>EXAMPLE</h3>\n<pre>\n<b>Input</b>\n2\n3\n3 3\n2 2\n1 1\n0 0\n3\n10 10\n5 12\n6 13\n11 11\n<b>Output</b>\n6\n3\n</pre>",
